00:14:29,433 --> 00:14:30,415
Yes, absolutely.

155
00:14:31,216 --> 00:14:31,616
Thank you.

156
00:14:32,097 --> 00:14:32,237
Yep.

157
00:14:37,945 --> 00:14:43,029
Okay, so let's jump right into talking about the Climate Action and Adaptation Plan.

158
00:14:44,430 --> 00:14:51,636
That's this giant book right here, actually, that was released.

159
00:14:52,717 --> 00:14:54,499
This is also available online, actually.

160
00:14:54,519 --> 00:14:59,343
I think I've sent the council members the PDF of this as well.

161
00:15:01,610 --> 00:15:14,551
But this was released in April of 2020 after lots of input from many residents of the city, all the different city departments, city council, lots of iterations of this.

162
00:15:16,859 --> 00:15:26,907
And the goal is not just to be carbon neutral, which is what you might think of a plan like this, but to do it in a way that makes the city more just, equitable, resilient, and healthy.

163
00:15:26,927 --> 00:15:35,735
And when I think of resilient, I tend to think of being able to respond quickly to a power outage or a flood or something like that.

164
00:15:36,335 --> 00:15:45,783
But we also want to help people be more resilient in their daily lives, to have access to food or other services so they can recover from things like job losses.

165
00:15:51,801 --> 00:15:55,282
But climate change will make any existing inequities worse.

166
00:15:56,002 --> 00:16:10,706
Some more intense storms, hotter temperatures, flooding will impact people's ability to get to work, to go to the grocery store, to have a heating and cooling system that works, to have power for medical equipment that they need.

167
00:16:11,846 --> 00:16:19,208
So it's really important that we do our part to reduce the intensity of climate change while also preparing residents for the impact of it.

168
00:16:24,697 --> 00:16:26,879
And this is from the climate action plan.

169
00:16:26,939 --> 00:16:30,661
So it's a little out of date now, but the general message hasn't changed.

170
00:16:31,422 --> 00:16:38,427
Buildings represent about 70% of our carbon emissions and transportation about 30% here in Medford.

171
00:16:39,528 --> 00:16:44,531
So we know what's most important for us to focus on in terms of reducing our carbon emissions.

172
00:16:45,952 --> 00:16:48,554
In large terms, we know what's most important to focus on.

173
00:16:51,916 --> 00:16:58,823
Now the Climate Action Plan breaks things down a little differently, more along the lines of the different departments in the city.

174
00:17:00,264 --> 00:17:14,458
We have topic areas of buildings and energy, ecosystems and natural environment, public health and transportation, and each area has different objectives and then strategies and actions to meet those objectives.

175
00:17:18,317 --> 00:17:21,018
And the very first action in the plan is you actually.

176
00:17:21,458 --> 00:17:24,860
So this is how important the city thinks that your work will be.

177
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:30,822
And one of the other actions listed here is to model greenhouse gas emissions.

178
00:17:31,442 --> 00:17:35,124
And that's something that I'd like to do over the next year or so.

179
00:17:36,364 --> 00:17:43,447
I'd like to hire a consultant to project how much we can expect each of these actions to save so we can really help prioritize what we do.

180
00:17:47,218 --> 00:18:04,245
So the buildings and energy section, it talks about access to healthy homes and places that are affordable, that use little energy, produce almost no climate pollution, and keep residents safe during extreme weather.

181
00:18:08,006 --> 00:18:09,707
And so some of the strategies here

182
00:18:11,073 --> 00:18:31,528
focus on diverse housing options and affordable housing options for all sizes of families, all income levels, high performance new buildings, so updating the zoning codes.

183
00:18:32,129 --> 00:18:34,050
And this is something that's actually coming up.

184
00:18:34,651 --> 00:18:39,975
The city's hiring a zoning consultant to do sort of an overhaul of the entire

185
00:18:41,251 --> 00:18:49,319
zoning, and so part of that will be making sure that climate is really considered in that zoning overhaul.

186
00:18:52,823 --> 00:18:56,447
Making new buildings flood resistant or flood resilient.

187
00:18:57,739 --> 00:19:12,576
So in areas that are likely to face floods in the future and that's different than areas that are in flood zones right now right so folks might not even necessarily be aware that in the future there they're projected to be in flood zones.

188
00:19:17,778 --> 00:19:42,536
Another buildings and energy strategy is adopting the net zero stretch, or we have the net zero stretch code advocating for an even better, what's called the specialized opt-in code, which the state actually did put forward and Medford actually did adopt earlier this month.

189
00:19:44,061 --> 00:19:53,187
This is something again for new buildings and major renovations to reduce their emissions.

190
00:19:54,528 --> 00:20:08,317
Then to lead by example by building any new municipal buildings to a real high standard of net zero energy, and that's something that the city did with the new library building shown here.

191
00:20:14,142 --> 00:20:20,827
New buildings are actually only a tiny part of the building stock here in Medford.

192
00:20:20,967 --> 00:20:24,990
Retrofitting existing buildings is actually even more important than that.

193
00:20:27,572 --> 00:20:36,579
Some of the strategies for existing buildings include encouraging fuel switching from fossil fuels to electricity.

194
00:20:39,135 --> 00:20:42,858
and encouraging energy efficiency in those buildings as well.

195
00:20:43,378 --> 00:20:48,741
This is part of what I said, that outreach campaign that I'm hoping that we'll be doing next year.

196
00:20:52,183 --> 00:20:54,365
Benchmarking and energy standards.

197
00:20:55,533 --> 00:21:14,169
Some other cities have done things where they require buildings over a certain size to report their energy usage each year, and then set standards saying that their energy or their emissions need to be below a certain threshold per square foot.

198
00:21:17,928 --> 00:21:32,890
And then providing tools and resources to property owners to help them to do these to do resilience retrofits as well, so preparing for the flooding, the higher temperatures, the power outages, things like that.

199
00:21:39,355 --> 00:21:50,533
And then also doing the same thing for our municipal buildings and so this is something that the city is working on all the time sort of piece by piece I mean right now I think there are multiple

200
00:21:51,506 --> 00:21:53,867
um, lighting upgrades going on.

201
00:21:53,947 --> 00:22:01,109
There are some weatherization upgrades that are happening, um, or will be happening in multiple city buildings.

202
00:22:01,169 --> 00:22:04,911
And so this is something that the city has been doing and continues to do.

203
00:22:04,991 --> 00:22:08,772
But we just we need to ramp up as as time goes by.

204
00:22:14,409 --> 00:22:23,185
And so we also need to, in addition to making sure that our buildings are energy efficient and low emission, we also need to power them with renewable energy.

